00:02:52.230 --> 00:02:59.459
&gt;&gt;Chris: David, I think that's a good question
for you.

00:02:59.459 --> 00:03:00.459
&gt;&gt;David: Sure.

00:03:00.459 --> 00:03:04.299
Actually, the session I came from right before
this was a session on Open Social and Open

00:03:04.299 --> 00:03:07.329
Social in the enterprise and some of the attraction
there and

00:03:07.329 --> 00:03:12.900
two days ago there was an Open Social meet
up that was hosted by MySpace in the city

00:03:12.900 --> 00:03:13.939
with a -- good.

00:03:13.939 --> 00:03:14.939
Good.

00:03:14.939 --> 00:03:19.389
I would have been there but I/O and the good
thing about scheduling that with I/O is many

00:03:19.389 --> 00:03:23.569
people were in town, bad thing is that many
of us who were busy with I/O weren't able

00:03:23.569 --> 00:03:24.569
to attend in person.

00:03:24.569 --> 00:03:27.559
But Mark and I were very involved in the planning.

00:03:27.559 --> 00:03:32.140
So Google strategy with Open Social is to
continue to use it in all the appropriate

00:03:32.140 --> 00:03:36.829
places Orchid obviously is heavily, heavily
using Open Social, iGoogle is using Open Social

00:03:36.829 --> 00:03:42.500
for all the applications that run on iGoogle,
the various APIs that the wire APIs where

00:03:42.500 --> 00:03:48.040
it makes sense for them to be aligned like
PoCo, portable contacts, are a part of Open

00:03:48.040 --> 00:03:50.260
Social and part of the Buzz APIs.

00:03:50.260 --> 00:03:56.040
So the core underlying standards that Open
Social and the rest of the Social Web are

00:03:56.040 --> 00:03:59.019
built on around OpenID and OAuth continue
to be driven pretty hard.

00:03:59.019 --> 00:04:04.040
So the strategy is continue to use it everywhere
it makes sense, which is a bunch of places,

00:04:04.040 --> 00:04:09.650
and continue to work with all the other folks
who are using Open Social, and other relevant

00:04:09.650 --> 00:04:13.430
standards to keep the standards moving towards
 – towards the ball and keep the ball moving

00:04:13.430 --> 00:04:14.489
towards the standards.

00:04:14.489 --> 00:04:18.340
&gt;&gt;Joseph: Yeah, I might just add that, uh,
opening up the Social Web is a

00:04:18.340 --> 00:04:20.040
Multi-pronged approach.

00:04:20.040 --> 00:04:23.550
There's a lot of different aspects of identity,
and sharing, and on-site, and offsite, and

00:04:23.550 --> 00:04:24.550
so forth.

00:04:24.550 --> 00:04:28.540
So anyone who's followed this space for a
while knows it's a somewhat messy and frothy

00:04:28.540 --> 00:04:32.100
cacophony of different overlapping standards
but they all are aware of each other and trying

00:04:32.100 --> 00:04:35.780
to play well together and I think that's actually
good because ultimately it gives developers

00:04:35.780 --> 00:04:38.950
a lot of flexibility in terms of building
blocks that they can mix and match together.

00:04:38.950 --> 00:04:43.390
So you see, for example, OAuth being used
with Open Social, RESTful APIs, and Discovery

00:04:43.390 --> 00:04:44.390
DOC.

00:04:44.390 --> 00:04:49.490
I mean, they're all very interrelated and
I think that's a healthy thing that's going

00:04:49.490 --> 00:04:50.490
to keep evolving.

00:04:50.490 --> 00:04:52.170
&gt;&gt;David: I actually wanna add one point that
comes up when we have this

00:04:52.170 --> 00:04:59.500
conversation internally and it really brought
home when we were chatting about it how quickly

00:04:59.500 --> 00:05:05.250
things are evolving in the space of the Social
Web and two and a half years ago when Open

00:05:05.250 --> 00:05:09.530
Social was first introduced by the set
of companies that the -- that defined that

00:05:09.530 --> 00:05:15.090
standard, the hottest thing in the
Social Web was running applications inside

00:05:15.090 --> 00:05:20.180
somebody else's site and – and putting social
applications inside a web site and that was

00:05:20.180 --> 00:05:22.320
the coolest, hottest, bestest thing.

00:05:22.320 --> 00:05:23.600
And it was.

00:05:23.600 --> 00:05:27.870
And that, now, is one of many interesting
things happening on the Social Web and it's

00:05:27.870 --> 00:05:29.740
far from the middle of the action.

00:05:29.740 --> 00:05:31.950
It's just -- it's one of many important things.

00:05:31.950 --> 00:05:38.250
So the technology that the – that the Open
Social standards community and -- and the

00:05:38.250 --> 00:05:42.790
Shindig implementation has invested most heavily
in really nails that problem and anywhere

00:05:42.790 --> 00:05:47.390
that – that somebody is trying solve that
problem, whether it's in the classic social

00:05:47.390 --> 00:05:52.420
sense it's something like Orchid in a sort
of extended sense in somewhere like Linkedin

00:05:52.420 --> 00:05:58.041
or somewhere like iGoogle whether it's, whether
it's more in an enterprise space which is

00:05:58.041 --> 00:06:03.040
the analogous thing where something like Atlassian
has re-factored their entire suite of development

00:06:03.040 --> 00:06:04.350
tools based on Open Social.

00:06:04.350 --> 00:06:07.180
Anywhere that that is the problem, that is
the answer.

00:06:07.180 --> 00:06:10.000
But the social web has become bigger than
that one problem.

00:06:10.000 --> 00:06:14.120
So the set of answers is bigger than that
one standard.

00:06:14.120 --> 00:06:18.660
&gt;&gt;Chris: And we have one question in the Buzz
as well that was kind of related to it.

00:06:18.660 --> 00:06:24.210
What are your experiences with implementing
these fast-moving standards compared to implementing

00:06:24.210 --> 00:06:27.750
standards coming out of the standard bodies?

00:06:27.750 --> 00:06:31.790
Have there been a lot of interoperability
issues?

00:06:31.790 --> 00:06:34.900
Are you having difficulties landing on the
right spec version?

00:06:34.900 --> 00:06:37.150
&gt;&gt;Sami: As we were implementing the Buzz APIs,
one of the things that was apparent is there's

00:06:37.150 --> 00:06:42.640
a lot of good movement in this standard space
but the standards are still young.

00:06:42.640 --> 00:06:49.450
And we're trying to build something that is
 -- is immediately useful to people so that

00:06:49.450 --> 00:06:55.010
they can do very interesting things with the
 -- with the Buzz infrastructure.

00:06:55.010 --> 00:07:02.400
However, we've had to introduce additional
extensions to the existing standards and one

00:07:02.400 --> 00:07:08.390
of our goals is to try to remove every proprietary
extension to these standards so that it allows

00:07:08.390 --> 00:07:17.640
anyone to become a -- a -- a core component
or a core player in the -- in the Social Web.

00:07:17.640 --> 00:07:18.730
[pause]

00:07:18.730 --> 00:07:20.920
&gt;&gt;Chris: Yeah.

00:07:20.920 --> 00:07:22.010
Cool.

