00:08:16.110 --> 00:08:17.110
What are the benefits of using these open
standards?

00:08:17.110 --> 00:08:18.850
Do you find that it's more difficult?

00:08:18.850 --> 00:08:21.850
Are you slower going?

00:08:21.850 --> 00:08:27.430
Having troubles coming up with specifications
with the community?

00:08:27.430 --> 00:08:30.080
Are there benefits to doing open or would
a closed system be better?

00:08:30.080 --> 00:08:31.080
[pause]

00:08:31.080 --> 00:08:33.090
&gt;&gt;David: Yes to all of the above.

00:08:33.090 --> 00:08:34.090
[laughing]

00:08:34.090 --> 00:08:35.600
DeWitt: That's a saluting question, Chris.

00:08:35.600 --> 00:08:37.000
Chris: Yeah, I know.

00:08:37.000 --> 00:08:38.000
DeWitt: No.

00:08:38.000 --> 00:08:40.140
We hate open here; right? I know.

00:08:40.140 --> 00:08:47.490
So the decision was made really early on with
Buzz to, to go all in on -- on the open side

00:08:47.490 --> 00:08:48.490
of this.

00:08:48.490 --> 00:08:54.750
I mean, I think for everybody here, there's
a desire to see what we're doing in Buzz,

00:08:54.750 --> 00:09:00.960
what we're doing in Open Social, implementable
literally by everybody.

00:09:00.960 --> 00:09:04.510
So it should not be a Google thing.

00:09:04.510 --> 00:09:08.630
So even if it was a little more difficult
and in some cases it is actual actually a

00:09:08.630 --> 00:09:16.940
lot more difficult toimplement to a community-lead,
openly-licensed spec, it's an investment that

00:09:16.940 --> 00:09:20.900
we're willing to make and we feel like we
get more out of it by investing up front and

00:09:20.900 --> 00:09:27.410
saying, hey, let's do Activity Streams, let's
do PoCo, let's do Media RSS. Knowing that

00:09:27.410 --> 00:09:35.140
what we'll end up with is a – a network
of sites and implementations rather than just

00:09:35.140 --> 00:09:36.180
Google.

00:09:36.180 --> 00:09:38.290
So harder, yes.

00:09:38.290 --> 00:09:39.290
Worth it, absolutely.

00:09:39.290 --> 00:09:45.310
I don't think anyone up here has any regrets
about this strategy.

00:09:45.310 --> 00:09:46.330
So.

00:09:46.330 --> 00:09:47.340
[pause]

00:09:47.340 --> 00:09:50.390
&gt;&gt;Joseph: We do get benefits from it too,
right?

00:09:50.390 --> 00:09:53.460
For example, take something like OAuth 2.0
which is being worked on right now as sort

00:09:53.460 --> 00:09:59.250
of a next generation way of accessing private
data securely and it's a lot simpler for developers.

00:09:59.250 --> 00:10:02.700
There is lots of really smart people outside
of Google who worked on that.

00:10:02.700 --> 00:10:05.392
We obviously have been working on it too and
so we get all the advantage of that insight,

00:10:05.392 --> 00:10:08.600
all of that field experience, all of that
trial and error.

00:10:08.600 --> 00:10:13.020
And, of course, all of the developers who
start using OAuth maybe to work with the property

00:10:13.020 --> 00:10:15.940
other than Google and then they come to Google
and realize they already know how to build

00:10:15.940 --> 00:10:20.000
that, especially since all those plumbing
layers tend to be the hard part to get right

00:10:20.000 --> 00:10:21.080
and it's not the fun part.

00:10:21.080 --> 00:10:24.000
The fun part is what you build on top of it
and so I think we absolutely see the benefits

00:10:24.000 --> 00:10:25.960
of it as well so that's why I think it's worth
investing.

00:10:25.960 --> 00:10:31.610
I mean, no one would think today to set up
a web API that wasn't over HTTP.

00:10:31.610 --> 00:10:33.871
It seems sorta silly to ask but in a way that's
kind of what we're building for the social

00:10:33.871 --> 00:10:34.871
era.

00:10:34.871 --> 00:10:37.080
&gt;&gt;David: I agree with all of that.

00:10:37.080 --> 00:10:40.450
The one -- one thing I wanna as add is 'cause
there were a couple of different threads in

00:10:40.450 --> 00:10:45.960
that question as asked, is the -- there was
a -- there was a comment about standard and

00:10:45.960 --> 00:10:51.200
there was a comment about interoperable and
I -- I wanna say that at least in my opinion

00:10:51.200 --> 00:10:54.540
one of those is very clearly a means and one
is an end; right?

00:10:54.540 --> 00:10:59.270
The end is mass -- is the maximum choice in
interoperability.

00:10:59.270 --> 00:11:01.000
That's the goal, right?

00:11:01.000 --> 00:11:05.750
And it just so happens that the best way that
I know or that I've seen in any industry to

00:11:05.750 --> 00:11:10.100
allow maximum choice in interoperability is
open standards 'cause everyone knows what

00:11:10.100 --> 00:11:13.630
to build and everyone knows that if they build
it they'll be allowed to use it and you need

00:11:13.630 --> 00:11:19.190
both of those to be true. And if -- and the
goal is, get maximum interoperability which

00:11:19.190 --> 00:11:20.190
is maximum choice.

00:11:20.190 --> 00:11:23.380
The means is open standards and that's the
best way we know to get there as an industry.

00:11:23.380 --> 00:11:24.380
&gt;&gt;Chris: Cool.

00:11:24.380 --> 00:11:25.380
Thank you.

00:11:25.380 --> 00:11:27.620
We have a question.

00:11:27.620 --> 00:11:28.850
&gt;&gt;Bill: Hi.

00:11:28.850 --> 00:11:30.710
My name's Neil.

00:11:30.710 --> 00:11:35.839
The Twitter library of Congress deal, that
was the gift that was announced on the 13th

00:11:35.839 --> 00:11:41.880
of April kinda got my mind reeling about long-term
data retention. I understand that it's open

00:11:41.880 --> 00:11:46.050
and everybody agrees to the terms of service
that our stuff's right out there but that

00:11:46.050 --> 00:11:51.890
type of deal could not be facilitated without
a lot of money and a lot of resources on one

00:11:51.890 --> 00:11:53.110
side and the other.

00:11:53.110 --> 00:11:58.270
So I guess I -- I was wondering if you could
speak to -- particularly on the Salmon protocol

00:11:58.270 --> 00:12:02.440
 -- if you ever thought of maybe an expiration
tag, something that will allow an author,

00:12:02.440 --> 00:12:07.780
at the time of publishing, of posting that
data, to put an expiration on it.

00:12:07.780 --> 00:12:12.990
And second -- second of all I guess -- I think
about these things in terms of robots.txt

00:12:12.990 --> 00:12:17.500
for web crawlers and that there's a no index
no follow convention and that's on a per page

00:12:17.500 --> 00:12:21.570
basis, not just in the robots.txt file as
a metatag.

00:12:21.570 --> 00:12:28.100
I -- I just -- I wanna kind of revisit that
idea that there's a possibility this data's

00:12:28.100 --> 00:12:33.700
retained forever and that necessarily wasn't
the intention and then the value of that data

00:12:33.700 --> 00:12:38.420
beyond the real-time now traveling into stale,
actually, does not – no longer serves a

00:12:38.420 --> 00:12:42.881
purpose or could serve a different purpose
in the future for the author than it was in

00:12:42.881 --> 00:12:44.750
the context of the real-time to interact.

00:12:44.750 --> 00:12:45.750
[pause]

00:12:45.750 --> 00:12:46.750
&gt;&gt;Chris: Cool.

00:12:46.750 --> 00:12:55.450
&gt;&gt;John: So I'll give a quick answer about
Salmon and hand it over -- there's a bunch

00:12:55.450 --> 00:13:06.361
of questions in there. So I think that Salmon
is extensible and you

00:13:06.361 --> 00:13:08.950
can put a lot of additional metadata in there
and a potential thing might be a, like, newspapers

00:13:08.950 --> 00:13:12.640
have this as stale after X date and we're
going to ask you to remove it after X date.

00:13:12.640 --> 00:13:15.660
The one thing about putting data out to the
universe is that once you broadcast it out,

00:13:15.660 --> 00:13:16.660
you can't be guaranteed anything.

00:13:16.660 --> 00:13:17.660
&gt;&gt;Bill: Sure.

00:13:17.660 --> 00:13:18.660
&gt;&gt;John: I mean, that's sort of obvious, right?

00:13:18.660 --> 00:13:20.750
It's like sending radio waves into outer space
they're out there potentially forever.

00:13:20.750 --> 00:13:26.300
But you can have signals that tell people
how to be polite and how to do the useful

00:13:26.300 --> 00:13:31.770
things with your data, and the services that
