stuff that you guys do in Buzz right now.

00:34:28.830 --> 00:34:37.399
How's that gonna appear in the API or will
I be able to dump a bunch of stuff at it and

00:34:37.399 --> 00:34:39.490
use it in my own apps?

00:34:39.490 --> 00:34:45.760
Because one of the things that's interesting
on the one hand, of course, is you get this

00:34:45.760 --> 00:34:49.820
Activity Stream of all this stuff in chronological
order.

00:34:49.820 --> 00:34:58.680
On the other hand, my experience in the Buzz
App has a bunch of condensed stuff and things

00:34:58.680 --> 00:35:05.650
that I imagine are gonna be made more relevant
to me over time based on different signals.

00:35:05.650 --> 00:35:15.220
So how can that experience I guess be made
portable for other people to embed in their

00:35:15.220 --> 00:35:16.340
external apps?

00:35:16.340 --> 00:35:19.720
&gt;&gt;Todd: That's a really good question.

00:35:19.720 --> 00:35:25.910
This is something that actually we're in the
middle of making many, many changes and improvements

00:35:25.910 --> 00:35:26.910
to.

00:35:26.910 --> 00:35:36.030
So today the way that it -- Buzz works when
you view it inside Gmail is that it's sorted

00:35:36.030 --> 00:35:40.420
by the last comment time.

00:35:40.420 --> 00:35:44.230
So any time someone leaves a new comment on
an item it jumps back onto the top.

00:35:44.230 --> 00:35:51.460
And the reason we did that is because we really
like the conversational nature of Buzz.

00:35:51.460 --> 00:35:54.430
We want things -- the items to be engaging
and involve conversation.

00:35:54.430 --> 00:36:00.370
We are in the process of re-thinking that
some.

00:36:00.370 --> 00:36:07.210
One of the things that we really want to do
is, is we want conversations to come back

00:36:07.210 --> 00:36:10.810
up to the top when they're interesting to
you.

00:36:10.810 --> 00:36:15.490
So because somebody that you're following
left a new comment, because the combination

00:36:15.490 --> 00:36:19.760
of activity that many people have done on
something makes it significantly interesting

00:36:19.760 --> 00:36:22.510
to pop back up to the top for you.

00:36:22.510 --> 00:36:29.700
So I think you'll see a lot of development
and sort of what we call -- we call this "bumping"

00:36:29.700 --> 00:36:33.800
and "personalized bumping" and it's something
we're gonna explore a lot in the future.

00:36:33.800 --> 00:36:38.310
While also -- another thing that we've heard
from users is, I just want the purely chronological

00:36:38.310 --> 00:36:39.450
view by post time stamp.

00:36:39.450 --> 00:36:46.490
So we want to also give -- offer, like, multiple
ways to view the Buzz stream, sort of slice

00:36:46.490 --> 00:36:47.520
it and dice it.

00:36:47.520 --> 00:36:50.640
And you'll see these corresponding changes
are happening into the API.

00:36:50.640 --> 00:36:58.500
But this is an area of really -- I think of
strong interest from the Buzz team.

00:36:58.500 --> 00:37:05.390
It's something that we're passionate about
and it's something that you'll see us explore

00:37:05.390 --> 00:37:06.390
a lot.

00:37:06.390 --> 00:37:07.390
&gt;&gt;Chris Messina: Thanks.

00:37:07.390 --> 00:37:08.390
Chris: Cool.

00:37:08.390 --> 00:37:10.710
We have another familiar face with a question.

00:37:10.710 --> 00:37:11.710
[laughing]

00:37:11.710 --> 00:37:12.890
&gt;&gt;Robert Scoble: Robert Scoble.

00:37:12.890 --> 00:37:18.310
I keep thinking about malleable social graphs
and the first one that showed me that -- the

00:37:18.310 --> 00:37:27.119
power of that is foursquare because if you
check in here, you only see people who are

00:37:27.119 --> 00:37:28.119
near here.

00:37:28.119 --> 00:37:32.690
Now, take that and there's two different pieces
to this question.

00:37:32.690 --> 00:37:40.320
One is, when are you gonna hook up to the
other data silos in the web, like foursquare,

00:37:40.320 --> 00:37:44.500
like tripIt, like other things that I'm showing
the web by my behaviors.

00:37:44.500 --> 00:37:47.720
My liking behaviors across the web, not just
on Buzz.

00:37:47.720 --> 00:37:48.720
That's one problem.

00:37:48.720 --> 00:37:53.740
And another problem is, how am I gonna discover
new people based on their expertise?

00:37:53.740 --> 00:37:58.280
For instance, if somebody's visited four barbecue
places in Austin, they've automatically set

00:37:58.280 --> 00:38:04.859
themselves apart from the crowd and become
an authority on Austin barbecue and I might

00:38:04.859 --> 00:38:13.910
want -- if I'm going to Austin or if I wanna
talk about barbecue, I only wanna hear from

00:38:13.910 --> 00:38:14.920
those people.

00:38:14.920 --> 00:38:24.339
I don't wanna hear from the rest of the people
who have no freaking clue about barbecue,

00:38:24.339 --> 00:38:25.339
right?

00:38:25.339 --> 00:38:34.200
And who haven't demonstrated the system that
they're an authority and credible on barbecue.

00:38:34.200 --> 00:38:38.750
How are you gonna build this malleable social
graph to both let us discover new people and

00:38:38.750 --> 00:38:42.280
see content only from people who are authoritative
and credible on -- on the world?

00:38:42.280 --> 00:38:46.040
&gt;&gt;Joseph: So I think the question was, do
I like barbecue and the answer is, yes.

00:38:46.040 --> 00:38:47.040
[laughing]

00:38:47.040 --> 00:38:48.040
&gt;&gt;Joseph: No, I –

00:38:48.040 --> 00:38:49.040
[laughing]

00:38:49.040 --> 00:38:51.011
&gt;&gt;Chris: So how could Robert discover you?

00:38:51.011 --> 00:38:59.839
&gt;&gt;Robert Scoble: Are you credible on barbecue,
and if you are, I wanna see your, like.

00:38:59.839 --> 00:39:01.140
&gt;&gt;Joseph: Right.

00:39:01.140 --> 00:39:02.140
Right.

00:39:02.140 --> 00:39:05.670
I'm a credible consumer of barbecue.

00:39:05.670 --> 00:39:13.630
&gt;&gt;Robert Scoble: But if haven't been to four
barbecue places, don't show me your thoughts

00:39:13.630 --> 00:39:14.630
on –

00:39:14.630 --> 00:39:15.630
&gt;&gt;Joseph: Totally.

00:39:15.630 --> 00:39:19.660
I -- I very much agree with everything you
said.

00:39:19.660 --> 00:39:28.720
When I talk about bridging the islands, one
of the things that -- not only is it so let

00:39:28.720 --> 00:39:39.190
users have choice to use the tools that they
want but it's so that individual tools can

00:39:39.190 --> 00:39:44.780
really special in individual social experiences.

00:39:44.780 --> 00:39:57.020
I think foursquare is a great example of something
that, by being its own experience, it can

00:39:57.020 --> 00:40:07.210
really nail that experience and I actually
choose to associate with a different set of

00:40:07.210 --> 00:40:12.930
friend on foursquare than I do on the other
tools I use.

00:40:12.930 --> 00:40:20.500
But of course I want that to then enrich the
rest of the things that I do.

00:40:20.500 --> 00:40:31.150
And that's honestly it's just something that
for us has been very early days but that's

00:40:31.150 --> 00:40:42.510
absolutely the -- the -- the payoff of allowing
all these different sites to flourish.

00:40:42.510 --> 00:40:55.070
You wanna make it really easy for me to go
to a place like foursquare and quickly sign

00:40:55.070 --> 00:41:03.869
up and find my friends and so forth and then
to use all that check-in history of me and

00:41:03.869 --> 00:41:06.950
my friends to inform me back on Google.

00:41:06.950 --> 00:41:11.619
It'd be nice to see it on Google Maps and
everywhere else.

00:41:11.619 --> 00:41:18.390
So that's the one thing is that I think absolutely
the more that there's two-way data flows,

00:41:18.390 --> 00:41:19.590
the way everyone wins, really.

00:41:19.590 --> 00:41:25.440
And then the second point was using that not
just based on my current social graph but

00:41:25.440 --> 00:41:30.270
actually based on interest and authority.

00:41:30.270 --> 00:41:37.400
I don't have anything particularly smart to
say about that.

00:41:37.400 --> 00:41:40.260
Maybe other people can.

00:41:40.260 --> 00:41:50.970
But I guess that I would point out that by
making the data open, one of the things you

00:41:50.970 --> 00:41:57.690
let people do is re-mix it in different ways
like that.

00:41:57.690 --> 00:42:09.400
So maybe Buzz is gonna have one way of presenting
data to you and that may or may not be appropriate

00:42:09.400 --> 00:42:20.839
to try to pivot on other axes but if the data's
available, other apps can try to do that and

00:42:20.839 --> 00:42:37.920
I think you've seen a lot of that in the Twitter
ecosystem where they'll take it and provide

00:42:37.920 --> 00:42:45.551
a completely different view that's not based
on time line but it's based on keyword or

00:42:45.551 --> 00:42:52.150
based on a set of people or location and I
think that's a great example of the kind of

00:42:52.150 --> 00:42:56.230
innovation you can unlock when you let the
data free.

00:42:56.230 --> 00:42:58.150
&gt;&gt; [Asking question in the background]

00:42:58.150 --> 00:43:01.590
&gt;&gt;Chris: So just to repeat the question so
YouTube picks up on it as well,

00:43:01.590 --> 00:43:02.590
Twitter has lists as a solution.

00:43:02.590 --> 00:43:04.970
Do you consider doing something similar?

00:43:04.970 --> 00:43:05.970
&gt;&gt;Todd: Yeah.

00:43:05.970 --> 00:43:12.970
The feature request of some kind of filters,
or lists, or groups, something along those

00:43:12.970 --> 00:43:21.210
lines is something that we've heard often
and that we're thinking about it and working

00:43:21.210 --> 00:43:22.210
on.

00:43:22.210 --> 00:43:26.560
Also, just one of the things you mentioned
is just the ability to see what you've liked.

00:43:26.560 --> 00:43:30.960
In Buzz, you can't -- I can't see what Robert
Scoble has liked.

00:43:30.960 --> 00:43:34.160
That's a feature that we're launching very
soon.

00:43:34.160 --> 00:43:36.559
Hopefully like next week or so.

00:43:36.559 --> 00:43:38.180
&gt;&gt; [Asking question in the background]

00:43:38.180 --> 00:43:39.180
&gt;&gt;Todd: That's correct.

00:43:39.180 --> 00:43:40.180
Yeah.

00:43:40.180 --> 00:43:41.180
So I think -- yeah.

00:43:41.180 --> 00:43:42.180
Interoperability is -- is –

00:43:42.180 --> 00:43:48.619
&gt;&gt;Joseph: You can imagine pulling those images
APIs for that stuff.

00:43:48.619 --> 00:44:03.470
In theory, all this stuff should flow and
you should be able to aggregate it all together.

00:44:03.470 --> 00:44:05.990
&gt;&gt;DeWitt: We just call those activities, right?

00:44:05.990 --> 00:44:12.090
The action of liking some entity is an activity
and then, as we develop protocols like Salmon,

00:44:12.090 --> 00:44:14.540
those activities can be federated.

00:44:14.540 --> 00:44:22.220
So you could imagine a world in which starring
something on twitter or liking it in Facebook

00:44:22.220 --> 00:44:25.800
gets propagated to you on whatever network
you're on.

00:44:25.800 --> 00:44:29.200
&gt;&gt;Joseph: It's also a good use case for Activity
Streams, right?

00:44:29.200 --> 00:44:36.000
Right now, almost all of the syndication between
web sites is just RSS and atom which really

00:44:36.000 --> 00:44:41.609
don't have innate notions of things like location
or liking and Activity Streams do.

00:44:41.609 --> 00:44:49.150
That's exactly the kind of richer semantics
you want so that I know that a geo located

00:44:49.150 --> 00:44:56.099
check-in can be on any service and I can still
aggregate it

00:44:56.099 --> 00:45:01.060
around a map or that it's a like and I can
aggregate that, or it's a shared

00:45:01.060 --> 00:45:02.060
link, or it's a photo.

00:45:02.060 --> 00:45:04.870
You don't have to do a custom integration
on a per-site basis.

00:45:04.870 --> 00:45:10.530
&gt;&gt;John: And, to follow on that, one of the
benefits to users of going and doing all these

00:45:10.530 --> 00:45:17.359
things and building up this data and making
it open in some cases just totally public

00:45:17.359 --> 00:45:22.700
is that they built up a reputation and the
fact that they -- this stuff is actually linkable

00:45:22.700 --> 00:45:35.280
to each other is a feature in these cases
because you can -- you can build up a reputation

00:45:35.280 --> 00:45:40.240
as the best person to talk to about barbecue,
and it doesn't matter which service it was

00:45:40.240 --> 00:45:46.000
that you used and it really shouldn't because
if you built a reputation somewhere, you should

00:45:46.000 --> 00:45:47.441
be able to carry that.

00:45:47.441 --> 00:45:49.720
It should be a portable reputation.

00:45:49.720 --> 00:45:50.720
[pause]

00:45:50.720 --> 00:46:00.500
&gt;&gt;Sami: One additional point I'd like to add
to that is, I mean, we're in a space where

00:46:00.500 --> 00:46:12.190
the -- we have a theories on what the answers
are going to be and if you have ideas or things

00:46:12.190 --> 00:46:25.640
that you wanna build based on the social infrastructure
that -- that we're building and it's -- and

00:46:25.640 --> 00:46:32.420
what we're building isn't -- doesn't make
that available, it'll be great if you reach

00:46:32.420 --> 00:46:41.710
out to us so that we can figure out ways to
make -- to help you build these very new innovative

00:46:41.710 --> 00:46:46.430
use cases because not all innovation is going
to come out of Google.

00:46:46.430 --> 00:46:52.869
The beauty of – of having APIs is that everyone
participates in -- in innovating in this space.

00:46:52.869 --> 00:46:54.970
So please reach out.

00:46:54.970 --> 00:46:56.010
&gt;&gt;Chris: Cool.

